          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Trumpâ€™s next round of tariffs </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/trumps-next-round-of-tariffs.png" alt="US President Donald Trump speaks to the press after signing a proclamation renaming the Gulf of Mexico as the Gulf of America aboard Air Force One" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"> US President Donald Trump speaks to the press after signing a proclamation renaming the Gulf of Mexico as the Gulf of America aboard Air Force One. Credits: Roberto Schmidt/ AFP </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;"><strong>Summary: President Trump plans to impose 25% tariffs on all steel and aluminum imports. Key trade partners respond differently, reflecting uneven trade interests. </strong></p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Donald Trump announced that he would impose 25% tariffs on all <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-11-02-2025-h2-2-steel-and-aluminum-imports" target="_blank">steel and aluminum imports</a>, including those from Canada and Mexico, as part of a broader trade policy overhaul. This move adds to existing duties, and Trump said he would announce "reciprocal tariffs" to match his government's levies to the rates charged by other countries on US products.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Canada and Mexico, the US's largest steel and aluminum suppliers, will be most impacted. The UK, which exports 10% of its steel to the US, warned of a "devastating blow" to its industry. Meanwhile, Australia is lobbying for an exemption, arguing its exports support American jobs and shared defense interests in the Indo-Pacific region. The US trade deficit widened last year to nearly $920 billion.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Trumpâ€™s tariff plans have created uncertainty for businesses and foreign negotiators. Unlike past administrations that used tariffs selectively, he now threatens broad measures, even on goods the US doesnâ€™t produce. He claims tariffs will offset budget deficits and trade losses while also leveraging them to force negotiations on issues like immigration and drug trafficking, as seen with Canada and Mexico.</p>
        </mj-text>
