        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;"><strong>Summary: Sudanâ€™s attempt to form a new government is rocky as the coalition splits into factions. Taqadum claims that each faction will operate independently under different political structures. </strong></p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Sudanâ€™s largest civilian political coalition, Taqadum, <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-11-02-2025-h3-3-split-into-two-factions" target="_blank">split into two factions</a> on Monday due to disagreements over forming a government in areas controlled by the paramilitary Rapid Support Forces (RSF). The RSF has been at war with the army since April 2023. Taqadum announced that each faction would operate independently under a separate name and political structure, further deepening divisions in Sudanâ€™s civilian political landscape.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Gen Burhan, Sudanâ€™s de facto ruler, sought diplomatic support to establish the new government as the army regained control of parts of Khartoum and Gezira. He met with political allies and proposed a "technocratic wartime government" led by a prime minister. The plan introduced a peace roadmap outlining steps for a transitional government, civilian leadership, and peaceful dialogue with RSF for free and fair elections.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">The war began after tensions between Burhan and RSF leader Gen Mohamed Hamdan Dagalo escalated over Sudanâ€™s governance. Since then, the conflict has displaced 12 million people, killed thousands, and caused the worst humanitarian crisis. Despite recent army advances, the RSF still controls much of western Sudan, where heavy fighting continues as it strengthens its hold over Darfur.
        </mj-text>
