          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Over 200,000 protesters gathered in Munich to <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-11-02-2025-br1-4-oppose-far-right-extremism" target="_blank">oppose far-right extremism</a> ahead of Germanyâ€™s general election on February 23. Demonstrators expressed outrage over the recent cooperation between the conservative Christian Democratic Union (CDU) and the far-right AfD in the Bundestag. Many view this as a violation of Germanyâ€™s long-standing policy against working with extremist parties.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">AfD, an anti-immigrant party, is currently polling second. CDU leader Friedrich Merz faced backlash after relying on AfD support twice last week, including for an immigration reform bill. Merz defended his decisions, arguing that "a right decision doesnâ€™t become wrong just because the wrong people support it." Activist groups, religious institutions, and Munich soccer clubs, including FC Bayern, supported the demonstration. </p>
        </mj-text>
