          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">What is the concept of resource nationalism?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/what-is-the-concept-of-resource-nationalism.png" alt="A map depicting the resource nationalism index" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"> A map depicting the resource nationalism index. Credits: Verisk Maplecroft </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;"><a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-11-02-2025-f1-6-resource-nationalism" target="_blank">Resource nationalism</a> refers to how governments exert control over their natural resources to maximize national benefits. This can look like direct state ownership, strict regulations on foreign companies, or policies that prioritize domestic resource processing over raw material exports. The concept is neither inherently good nor bad. Nations use a rather strategic approach to manage their resource wealth.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">A classic example would be Venezuela's nationalization of its oil industry. In the early 2000s, the government seized control of private oil operations to increase state revenue and fund social programs. While this move initially boosted public spending, it also discouraged foreign investment. Similarly, Indonesia imposed strict export bans on unprocessed nickel, while Zambia expanded state control over its copper mines to get a share of profits.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">While resource nationalism allows nations to assert sovereignty over their wealth, it can also create geopolitical tensions and market uncertainties, particularly for countries dependent on these resources. Additionally, resource-rich nations often renegotiate contracts when commodity prices rise, as seen in the Middle Eastâ€™s oil industry, where governments have historically revised agreements to secure greater profits. </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
